The more functional approach would be to use recursion.

    fun =
      -&gt;(acc = [], arr, map, fun) {
        arr.empty? ? acc : fun.(acc &lt;&lt; map.(arr.shift), arr, map, fun)
      }
    # #&lt;Proc:0x000055ab64333fa0@(pry):12 (lambda)&gt;

And for any mapper (e. g. square root,) use it like:

    fun.([1,2,3,4,5], -&gt;(e) { e ** 2 }, fun)
    # [1, 4, 9, 16, 25]

Please note! This approach _mutates_ the initial array, so it should be explicitly `array.dup`ed  before passing to the function. To eliminate the necessity to pass the function itself through _and_ leave the initial array intact, we would need a wrapper.


    fun =
      -&gt;(acc = [], arr, map, fun) {
        arr.empty? ? acc : fun.(acc &lt;&lt; map.(arr.shift), arr, map, fun)
      }
    # #&lt;Proc:0x000055ab64333fa0@(pry):12 (lambda)&gt;
    mapper = -&gt;(arr, map) { fun.([], arr.dup, map, fun) }

And use it like:

    arr = [1,2,3,4,5]
    mapper.(arr, -&gt;(e) { e ** 2 })
    # [1, 4, 9, 16, 25]
    arr
    # [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

